SENATE BILL DRS15196-MUf-27
Short Title: NC Debt Settlement Services Act. (Public)
Sponsors: Senators Johnson, Overcash, and Jackson (Primary Sponsors).
Referred to:
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO LICENSE, EXAMINE, AND REGULATE DEBT SETTLEMENT SERVICES IN
3 THE STATE OF NORTH CAROLINA.
4 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
5 SECTION 1. Chapter 53 of the General Statutes is amended by adding a new Article
6 to read:
7 "Article 26.
8 "North Carolina Debt Settlement Services Act.
9 "§ 53-441. Title.
10 This Article may be cited as the North Carolina Debt Settlement Services Act.
11 "§ 53-442. Definitions.
12 In this Article, the following definitions apply:
13 (1) Commission. – The State Banking Commission.
14 (2) Commissioner. – The Commissioner of Banks.
15 (3) Consumer reporting agency. – Defined in 15 U.S.C. § 1681a(f).
16 (4) Covered military member. – A member of the Armed Forces to which either
17 of the following applies:
18 a. The member is on active duty for a period of more than 30 days, as
19 defined in 10 U.S.C. § 101(d).
20 b. The member is on active Guard and Reserve duty, as defined in 10
21 U.S.C. § 101(d), with a rank of E4 or below.
22 (5) Creditor. – Includes persons that extend credit to, or persons that service loans
23 made to, debtors. This term does not include doctors, lawyers, or other
24 professionals who receive payment for their services in installments or
25 persons whose only participation in a credit transaction is to honor a credit
26 card.
27 (6) Debt collector. – A debt collector, as defined in 15 U.S.C. § 1692a, or a
28 collection agency, as defined in G.S. 58-70-15.
29 (7) Debt management organization. – An organization that satisfies all of the
30 following requirements:
31 a. Provides individualized credit counseling and budgeting assistance to
32 a debtor without charge prior to the debtor's enrollment in a debt
33 management plan.
34 b. Determines that the debtor has the financial ability to make payments
35 to complete the debt management plan and that the plan is suitable for
36 the debtor.
*DRS15196-MUf-27*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 c. Disburses the debtor's funds to creditors pursuant to a debt
2 management plan that the debtor has paid for with nominal
3 consideration and has agreed to in a record.
4 d. Provides to the debtor, periodically and on no less than a quarterly
5 basis, an individualized accounting for the most recent period of all of
6 the debtor's payments and disbursements under the debt management
7 plan and all charges paid by the debtor.
8 e. Does not directly or indirectly require the debtor to purchase other
9 services or materials as a condition to participating in the debt
10 management plan.
11 f. Does not receive a payment, commission, or other benefit for referring
12 the debtor to a provider of services.
13 g. Is accredited by an accrediting organization that the Commissioner of
14 Banks approves as being independent and nationally recognized for
15 providing accreditation to organizations that provide credit counseling
16 and debt management services.
17 (8) Debt settlement services. – Any action or negotiation initiated or taken on
18 behalf of a debtor with any creditor of the debtor for the purpose of obtaining
19 debt forgiveness of all or a portion of the credit extended by the creditor to the
20 debtor or a reduction of payments, charges, or fees payable by the debtor. With
21 respect to student loan forgiveness or student loan payment reduction
22 programs established under federal or State law and widely available to
23 similarly situated debtors at no cost, the facilitation of enrollment in or
24 qualification for these programs does not constitute an action or negotiation.
25 (9) Debtor. – An individual who resides in this State or an entity registered to do
26 business in this State. The term includes two or more individuals who are
27 jointly or severally, or jointly and severally, indebted to a creditor.
28 (10) Duplicate original. – An exact copy with signatures created by the same
29 impression as the original, an exact copy bearing an original signature, or, in
30 the case of an electronic transaction, an electronic version with electronic
31 signatures.
32 (11) Electronic signature. – Defined in G.S. 66-312.
33 (12) Licensee. – A person licensed under this Article.
34 (13) Nominal consideration. – A fee to cover the cost of administering a debt
35 management plan not to exceed forty dollars ($40.00) for origination or setup
36 of the debt management plan and ten percent (10%) of the monthly payment
37 disbursed under the debt management plan, not to exceed forty dollars
38 ($40.00) per month.
39 (14) Principal. – A person that, directly or indirectly, owns or controls ten percent
40 (10%) or more of the outstanding stock of a corporation or a ten percent (10%)
41 or greater interest in a person.
42 "§ 53-443. Rules by Commissioner.
43 The Commissioner may make rules to implement this Article.
44 "§ 53-444. License requirement; exceptions.
45 (a) No person shall engage in the business of providing or offering to provide debt
46 settlement services to any debtor, whether or not the person has an office, facility, agent, or other
47 physical presence in the State, unless the person obtains from the Commissioner a license issued
48 pursuant to this Article. This Article does not apply to any bank, savings institution, credit union,
49 refund anticipation loan act licensee under Article 20 of this Chapter, trust company doing
50 business under Chapter 53C of the General Statutes, savings and loan association doing business
51 under Chapter 54 or 54B of the General Statutes, savings bank doing business under Chapter 54C
Page 2 DRS15196-MUf-27

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 of the General Statutes, consumer finance licensee under Article 15 of this Chapter, or any person
2 licensed to practice law in this State.
3 (b) A debt management organization is not required to be licensed under this Article if it
4 offers to provide or provides debt settlement services solely in connection with offering to
5 provide or providing debt management plans. A nonprofit organization providing credit
6 counseling services that satisfies the requirements of 26 U.S.C. § 501(q) is also not required to
7 be licensed under this Article.
8 (c) This Article shall be construed by the Commissioner to promote sound personal
9 financial advice and management.
10 "§ 53-445. Application for license; form; content; fee.
11 (a) An application for a license under this Article shall be made in a record, under oath,
12 and on a form provided by the Commissioner.
13 (b) The application shall include all of the following:
14 (1) The name and address of the applicant and the following:
15 a. If the applicant is a partnership, firm, or association, the name and
16 address of each partner or member.
17 b. If the applicant is a corporation or limited liability company, the name
18 and address of each director, member, registered agent, and principal.
19 c. If the applicant is a business trust, the name and address of each trustee
20 and beneficiary.
21 (2) The name and address of each manager and officer of the applicant.
22 (3) The address of each location of the applicant.
23 (4) The financial statements of the applicant.
24 (5) A current copy of the applicant's standard debt settlement services agreement.
25 (6) The applicant's consent to a federal and State criminal history record check
26 and a set of the applicant's fingerprints in a form acceptable to the
27 Commissioner. In the case of an applicant that is a person other than a natural
28 person, each individual who has control of the applicant or who is the
29 qualifying individual or a branch manager shall consent to a federal and State
30 criminal history record check and submit a set of that individual's fingerprints.
31 (7) Payment of an application fee of two thousand dollars ($2,000). The
32 application fee shall not be refundable and shall not be abated by surrender,
33 suspension, or revocation of the license.
34 (8) Any other information required by the Commissioner concerning the financial
35 responsibility, background, experience, and activities of the applicant and the
36 persons described in this section.
37 "§ 53-446. Surety bond.
38 (a) Applicants shall be required to post a surety bond with the Commissioner at the time
39 of the application for licensure and each licensee shall maintain a surety bond in the amount of
40 one million dollars ($1,000,000).
41 (b) The surety bond shall be in a form satisfactory to the Commissioner and shall run to
42 the State for the benefit of any claimants against the licensee to secure the faithful performance
43 of the obligations of the licensee with respect to debt settlement engagements. The Commissioner
44 has the discretion to require the applicant to obtain additional insurance coverage to address
45 related cybersecurity risks inherent in the applicant's business model as it relates to debt
46 settlement engagements and to the extent these risks are not within the scope of the required
47 surety bond.
48 (c) The aggregate liability of the surety in no event shall exceed the principal sum of the
49 bond. Claimants against the licensee may themselves bring suit directly on the security bond, or
50 the Commissioner may bring suit on behalf of claimants, either in one action or in successive
51 actions.
DRS15196-MUf-27 Page 3

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (d) The surety bond shall remain in effect until cancellation, which may occur only after
2 90 days' written notice to the Commissioner. Cancellation does not affect any liability incurred
3 or accrued during that period.
4 (e) The surety bond shall remain in place for no less than five years after the licensee's
5 debt settlement operations cease in this State. However, the Commissioner may permit the surety
6 bond to be reduced or eliminated prior to that time to the extent of the amount of the licensee's
7 outstanding enrolled debt.
8 (f) The surety bond proceeds are deemed by operation of law to be held in trust for the
9 benefit of the debtors in a debt settlement engagement in the event of the bankruptcy of the
10 licensee.
11 "§ 53-447. Qualifications.
12 (a) After investigating an applicant, the Commissioner shall issue to the applicant a
13 license at the locations specified in the application if the Commissioner finds all of the following:
14 (1) The financial responsibility, character, reputation, experience, and general
15 fitness of the applicant and its members, officers, directors, trustees, and
16 principals warrant belief that the business will be operated efficiently and
17 fairly, in the public interest, and in accordance with law.
18 (2) The applicant has made acceptable provision for the avoidance of conflicts of
19 interest.
20 (3) No more than one-third of the board of directors or managing members are
21 employees, officers, members, principals, trustees, directors, agents, or other
22 representatives of organizations that grant credit to consumers.
23 (4) The applicant is not the subject of any pending material administrative
24 proceedings by any governmental authority and has not received a materially
25 adverse determination in any past administrative proceedings by any
26 governmental authority. The Commissioner has sole discretion to determine
27 the materiality of any proceedings or determinations.
28 (5) The applicant has complied with this Article and any rules adopted under it.
29 (b) If the Commissioner fails to make these findings, no license shall be issued, and the
30 Commissioner shall notify the applicant of the denial and the reasons for the denial.
31 (c) A license shall not be issued to a creditor or debt collector.
32 "§ 53-448. Licenses; places of business; changes.
33 (a) Each license shall state the address or addresses at which the business is to be
34 conducted and shall fully state the legal name of the licensee, as well as any assumed business
35 name by which the licensee is operating in this State, whether physically or electronically. Each
36 license shall be posted prominently in each place of business of the licensee. Licenses are not
37 transferable or assignable, by operation of law or otherwise. No licensee shall use any name in
38 this State other than the legal name or assumed business name set forth in the license.
39 (b) No licensee shall open an additional office or relocate any place of business without
40 prior approval of the Commissioner. Applications for this approval shall be made in a record on
41 a form provided by the Commissioner and shall be accompanied by payment of a five hundred
42 dollar ($500.00) nonrefundable application fee. The application shall be approved unless the
43 Commissioner finds that the applicant has not conducted business under this Article efficiently,
44 fairly, in the public interest, and in accordance with law. The application is deemed approved if
45 notice to the contrary has not been mailed by the Commissioner to the applicant within 30 days
46 of the date the application is received by the Commissioner; however, the Commissioner may
47 extend this period for good cause. After approval, the applicant shall give notice in a record to
48 the Commissioner within 20 days of the commencement of business at the additional location or
49 relocated place of business.
Page 4 DRS15196-MUf-27

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (c) A licensee shall notify the Commissioner in a record of the closing of any business
2 location within 20 days of the closing. A licensee shall provide any other information regarding
3 the closing that the Commissioner requires.
4 (d) A license shall remain in force until it has been surrendered, revoked, or suspended.
5 The surrender, revocation, or suspension of a license does not affect any preexisting legal right
6 or obligation of the licensee.
7 "§ 53-449. Acquisition of control; application.
8 (a) Except as otherwise provided in this section, no person shall acquire, directly or
9 indirectly, twenty-five percent (25%) or more of the ownership of a licensee, or, if the licensee
10 is a corporation, twenty-five percent (25%) of its voting shares, unless the person first does all of
11 the following:
12 (1) Files an application with the Commissioner in a form prescribed by the
13 Commissioner.
14 (2) Submits any information required by the Commissioner concerning the
15 financial responsibility, background, experience, and activities of the person,
16 its directors, officers, trustees, beneficiaries, principals, and members, and any
17 proposed new directors, officers, principals, or members of the licensee.
18 (3) Pays an application fee in an amount prescribed by the Commissioner.
19 (b) After investigating the applicant, the Commissioner shall permit the applicant to
20 acquire the interest in the licensee if it finds that the applicant and its directors, officers, members,
21 trustees, beneficiaries, and principals, and any proposed new directors, officers, principals, or
22 members of the licensee have the financial responsibility, character, reputation, experience, and
23 general fitness to warrant belief that the business will be operated efficiently and fairly, in the
24 public interest, and in accordance with law. The Commissioner shall grant or deny the application
25 within 60 days from the date a completed application accompanied by the required fee is filed
26 unless the period is extended by the Commissioner. If the Commissioner extends this period, the
27 Commissioner shall notify the applicant of the reasons for the extension. If the application is
28 denied, the Commissioner shall notify the applicant of the denial and the reasons for the denial.
29 (c) This section does not apply to any of the following:
30 (1) The acquisition of an interest in a licensee, directly or indirectly, including an
31 acquisition by merger or consolidation, by or with another licensee.
32 (2) The acquisition of an interest in a licensee, directly or indirectly, including an
33 acquisition by merger or consolidation, by or with a person affiliated through
34 common ownership with the licensee.
35 (3) The acquisition of an interest in a licensee by a person by devise, descent,
36 survivorship, or operation of law.
37 (d) A person acquiring an interest in a licensee in a transaction described in subsection
38 (c) of this section shall send written notice to the Commissioner of the acquisition within 30 days
39 of its closing.
40 "§ 53-450. Retention of books, accounts, and records; responding to the Commissioner.
41 (a) A licensee shall maintain in its offices any books, accounts, and records required by
42 the Commissioner to determine whether the licensee is complying with this Article and rules
43 adopted under it. These books, accounts, and records shall be maintained separately from any
44 other business in which the licensee is involved. Records relating to debt settlement services
45 agreements shall be retained for at least three years after the debt settlement services agreements
46 are terminated. To safeguard the privacy of debtors, records containing personal financial
47 information shall be shredded, incinerated, or otherwise disposed of in a secure manner.
48 Licensees may arrange for disposal from a business record destruction vendor.
49 (b) If the Commissioner requests a response in a record from the licensee, or any books,
50 accounts, records, or other documents from a licensee, the licensee shall submit a response in a
51 record, along with the requested documents, within the time period specified by the
DRS15196-MUf-27 Page 5

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 Commissioner. In determining this time period or whether to extend this time period, the
2 Commissioner shall consider the volume and complexity of the request. If the Commissioner
3 does not specify a time period, the licensee shall respond within 30 days of the request.
4 (c) No person shall make any false statement or knowingly and willfully make any
5 omission of a material fact in connection with any information or report filed with the
6 Commissioner or another governmental agency, or in connection with any oral or written
7 communication with the Commissioner or another governmental agency. If the information
8 contained in any document filed with the Commissioner or at the direction of the Commissioner
9 becomes inaccurate or incomplete in any material respect, the licensee or exempt person shall
10 within 30 days file a correcting amendment to the information contained in the document.
11 (d) The Commissioner may, by rule, impose terms and conditions under which the
12 records and files of a licensee may be maintained outside this State. A principal place of business
13 shall not be located at an individual's home or residence. A licensee shall maintain a record of
14 the principal place of business with the Commissioner and report any change of address of the
15 principal place of business or any branch office within 15 days after the change.
16 "§ 53-451. Annual report.
17 A licensee shall submit a report in a record to the Commissioner no later than 90 days after
18 the end of each calendar year. The report shall be made under oath and shall be in a form
19 prescribed by the Commissioner. The report shall contain any information required by the
20 Commissioner concerning the licensee's business and operations during the prior calendar year
21 as well as all of the following data:
22 (1) The number of debts and the delinquency status of each debt enrolled at the
23 time of contract enrollment for debt settlement services as follows:
24 a. Delinquent for 60 to 89 days.
25 b. Delinquent for 90 to 119 days.
26 c. Delinquent for 120 to 179 days.
27 d. Delinquent for 180 days or more.
28 (2) The number of debtors enrolled in debt settlement services in the prior
29 calendar year.
30 (3) The number of debts enrolled by debtors in debt settlement services in the
31 prior calendar year.
32 (4) The total dollar amount of debts placed in debt settlement services with the
33 licensee.
34 (5) The number and dollar amount of settlements paid by debtors enrolled in debt
35 settlement services.
36 (6) The number of debts enrolled in debt settlement services that failed to reach
37 settlement.
38 (7) The number of debtors that had a contract with the licensee at some point
39 during the prior calendar year that have filed for bankruptcy under the United
40 States Bankruptcy Code, Title 11 of the United States Code.
41 (8) Total dollar amount of fees for all charges to debtors enrolled in debt
42 settlement services.
43 "§ 53-452. Other reporting requirements.
44 (a) Within 15 days after any of the following events, a licensee shall submit a report in a
45 record to the Commissioner describing the event and its expected impact on its business:
46 (1) The filing of bankruptcy, reorganization, or receivership proceedings by or
47 against the licensee.
48 (2) The institution of administrative proceedings against the licensee by any
49 governmental authority.
50 (3) The institution of an action against the licensee by the Attorney General or
51 any other governmental authority.
Page 6 DRS15196-MUf-27

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (4) Any felony indictment of the licensee or any of its members, partners,
2 directors, officers, trustees, beneficiaries, or principals, if known.
3 (5) Any felony conviction of the licensee or any of its members, partners,
4 directors, officers, trustees, beneficiaries, or principals, if known.
5 (6) Any other event prescribed by the Commissioner by rule.
6 (b) Within 30 days after a judgment against a licensee in a civil action relating to the debt
7 settlement services agreement with a debtor, the licensee shall submit a report in a record to the
8 Commissioner describing the event and its expected impact on the business of the licensee.
9 (c) Within 10 days after receipt of a qualified audit, a licensee shall notify the
10 Commissioner and describe what steps are being taken to address the concerns raised in the audit.
11 "§ 53-453. Investigations; examinations.
12 (a) The Commissioner may, as often as the Commissioner deems necessary, investigate
13 and examine the affairs, business, premises, records, and filed complaints related to any person
14 licensed or required to be licensed under this Article to determine whether the business complies
15 with this Article and rules adopted under it. Examinations of licensees shall be conducted at least
16 once every three years. During an investigation or examination, the owners, members, officers,
17 directors, partners, trustees, beneficiaries, and employees of the person being investigated or
18 examined shall, upon demand of the Commissioner, afford full access to all premises, books,
19 records, and information.
20 (b) The Commissioner may do one or more of the following pursuant to an investigation
21 or examination under this section:
22 (1) Issue subpoenas, including subpoenas duces tecum.
23 (2) Compel the attendance of witnesses and the production of any documents.
24 (3) Administer oaths, conduct hearings, and transcribe testimony.
25 (4) Give publicity to the examination or investigation if the Commissioner deems
26 it best for the public interest.
27 "§ 53-454. Confidential information; shared agreements with other governmental agencies.
28 (a) Notwithstanding any State law to the contrary, the Commissioner shall report
29 enforcement actions under this Article and may report other relevant information.
30 (b) The Commissioner may enter agreements or sharing arrangements with other
31 governmental agencies, the Conference of State Bank Supervisors, or other associations
32 representing governmental agencies and may share otherwise confidential information pursuant
33 to these written agreements.
34 (c) The requirements of G.S. 53C-2-7 regarding the privacy or confidentiality of any
35 information or material provided under subsections (a) and (b) of this section, and any privilege
36 arising under any other federal or State law with respect to the information or material, continue
37 to apply to the information or material after it has been disclosed to an entity described in
38 subsection (a) or (b) of this section. Information or material held by the entity is not subject to
39 disclosure under any State law governing the disclosure to the public of information held by an
40 officer or agency of the State. The entities described in subsections (a) and (b) of this section
41 may share information and material with all State and federal regulatory officials with debt
42 settlement industry oversight authority without the loss of privilege or the loss of confidentiality
43 protections provided by State or federal law.
44 (d) Any provision of Chapter 132 of the General Statutes relating to the disclosure of
45 confidential supervisory information or of any information or material described in subsection
46 (a) of this section that is inconsistent with this section is superseded by the requirements of this
47 section.
48 (e) The confidentiality provisions contained in subsection (c) of this section do not apply
49 to information or material relating to the employment history of and publicly adjudicated
50 disciplinary and enforcement actions for debt settlement service providers.
51 "§ 53-455. Annual fees; reimbursement of travel expenses.
