1 (a) To defray the costs of the regulation of licensees, a licensee shall pay an annual fee
2 of one thousand dollars ($1,000). A licensee shall also pay to the Commissioner an assessment
3 not to exceed eighteen dollars ($18.00) per one hundred thousand dollars ($100,000) of debt
4 enrolled in debt settlement services. All fees shall be assessed on or after November 1 each
5 calendar year, and all fees shall be paid by the licensee on or before July 1 following each
6 assessment.
7 (b) In addition to the annual fee, if it becomes necessary to examine the books, accounts,
8 and records of a licensee at a location outside this State, the licensee is liable for and shall pay to
9 the Commissioner, within 30 days after the presentation of an itemized statement, the actual
10 travel and subsistence expenses incurred on account of the Commissioner's examination, or shall
11 pay a per diem to the Commissioner at a rate approved by the Commission.
12 "§ 53-456. Licensees providing debt settlement services; prohibited and required business
13 methods.
14 A licensee engaged in the business of providing or offering to provide debt settlement
15 services to any debtor shall comply with all of the following requirements:
16 (1) Each debt settlement services agreement shall be in a record and shall be
17 signed by the debtor and an individual representing the licensee. The
18 agreement may be signed by the parties either in writing or electronically. The
19 agreement shall set forth all of the following:
20 a. The name and address of both the debtor and the licensee.
21 b. A full description of all services to be performed for the debtor by the
22 licensee.
23 c. A clear explanation, highlighted in bold type, of the costs to the debtor.
24 d. A statement that the debt settlement services agreement may be
25 terminated for any reason by the debtor and that the debtor has no
26 obligation to continue the arrangement unless satisfied with the
27 services provided.
28 e. An explanation of the method of dispute resolution under the
29 agreement.
30 f. An explanation of the obligations of the debtor and the licensee.
31 g. Notification of privacy policies in compliance with State and federal
32 law.
33 h. The phone number, email, and physical address of the North Carolina
34 Commissioner of Banks and the North Carolina Consumer Protection
35 Division of the North Carolina Office of Justice for the purpose of
36 filing complaints related to debt settlement services.
37 (2) A licensee shall give to the debtor a duplicate original of the agreement
38 executed by the debtor and licensee upon execution.
39 (3) A licensee shall not request or receive payment or other compensation for any
40 debt settlement services until and unless:
41 a. The licensee has negotiated, settled, reduced, or otherwise altered the
42 terms of at least one debt pursuant to the debt settlement services
43 agreement.
44 b. The debtor has made at least one payment to a creditor following the
45 licensee's negotiation, settlement, reduction, or other alteration of at
46 least one debt owed by the debtor to that creditor.
47 (4) Prior to the execution of a debt settlement services agreement, a licensee shall
48 disclose to the debtor in a record, and retain a copy of, all of the following:
49 a. The amount of time necessary to achieve the represented results and,
50 to the extent that the services may include a settlement offer to any of
Page 8 DRS15196-MUf-27

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 the debtor's creditors or debt collectors, the time by which the licensee
2 will make a bona fide settlement offer to each of them.
3 b. To the extent that the services may include a settlement offer to any of
4 the debtor's creditors or debt collectors, the amount of money or the
5 percentage of each outstanding debt that the debtor shall accumulate
6 before the licensee will make a bona fide settlement offer to each of
7 them.
8 c. To the extent that any aspect of the debt settlement services relies upon
9 or results in the debtor's failure to make timely payments to creditors
10 or debt collectors, that the use of the debt settlement services will
11 likely adversely affect the debtor's creditworthiness, may result in the
12 debtor being subject to collections or sued by creditors or debt
13 collectors, and may increase the amount of money the debtor owes due
14 to the accrual of fees and interest.
15 (5) A licensee shall not require a debtor to execute a power of attorney as a
16 condition of receiving debt settlement services.
17 (6) A licensee shall not require a debtor to open an account with a depository
18 institution as a condition of receiving debt settlement services. A licensee may
19 request that a debtor open an account in connection with its provision of debt
20 settlement services so long as all of the following apply:
21 a. The debtor's funds are held in an account at a financial institution
22 insured by the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation or National
23 Credit Union Administration.
24 b. The debtor owns the funds held in the account and is paid accrued
25 interest on the account, if any.
26 c. The entity administering the account is not owned or controlled by, or
27 in any way affiliated with, the licensee.
28 d. The entity administering the account does not give or accept any
29 money or other compensation in exchange for referrals of business
30 from the licensee.
31 e. The debtor may withdraw from the debt settlement services at any time
32 without penalty and shall receive all funds in the account, other than
33 the fee earned by the licensee for completed services, if any, subject
34 to the limitations imposed by this Article.
35 (7) A licensee, or its affiliate, subsidiary, or partner, shall not receive a gift, bonus,
36 premium, reward, or other compensation, directly or indirectly, for advising,
37 arranging, or assisting a debtor in connection with obtaining any extension of
38 credit or other service from a creditor, except for educational or counseling
39 services required in connection with a government-sponsored program.
40 (8) A licensee shall not enroll a debtor in a debt settlement for a debt that is less
41 than 60 days delinquent, as determined by a consumer reporting agency.
42 (9) A licensee shall not enroll a debt for debt settlement services whose
43 origination date is less than 180 days from the date of enrollment.
44 (10) A licensee shall not instruct, encourage, or promote a debtor to obtain
45 additional extensions of credit as part of the enrollment for debt settlement
46 services.
47 (11) A licensee shall not solicit or advise a debtor or potential customer to default
48 on any loan.
49 (12) A licensee shall not send a cease-and-desist notice to a creditor of a debtor to
50 which the licensee is offering or providing debt settlement services.
