1 (13) A licensee shall not receive money from a debtor for transmission to a debtor's
2 creditors or engage in the business of providing or offering to provide debt
3 management plans to debtors unless the licensee is also licensed under Article
4 16B of this Chapter.
5 (14) A licensee shall not enroll a covered military member.
6 "§ 53-457. Fee for debt settlement services.
7 (a) If a licensee successfully reaches a settlement for a debt of a debtor, the licensee may
8 charge the debtor a fee that does not exceed either of the following:
9 (1) Fifteen percent (15%) of the principal amount of the debt.
10 (2) Twenty percent (20%) of the difference between the amount of the debt at the
11 time the licensee settles the debt and the amount to be paid by the debtor
12 pursuant to the settlement.
13 (b) A licensee shall not charge a debtor any other fee for providing debt settlement
14 services.
15 "§ 53-458. Advertising.
16 No person licensed or required to be licensed under this Article shall use or cause to be
17 published any advertisement that contains any false, misleading, or deceptive statement or
18 representation or identifies the person by any name other than the name set forth on the license
19 issued by the Commissioner.
20 "§ 53-459. Suspension or revocation of license.
21 (a) The Commissioner may suspend or revoke a license issued under this Article upon
22 any of the following grounds:
23 (1) Any ground for denial of a license under this Article.
24 (2) Any violation of the provisions of this Article or rules adopted under it, or a
25 violation of any other law applicable to the conduct of the licensee's business.
26 (3) A course of conduct consisting of the failure to perform debt settlement
27 services agreements.
28 (4) Conviction of a felony or misdemeanor involving fraud, misrepresentation, or
29 deceit.
30 (5) Entry of a judgment against the licensee involving fraud, misrepresentation,
31 or deceit.
32 (6) Entry of a federal or State administrative order against the licensee for
33 violation of any law related to the conduct of the licensee's business.
34 (7) Refusal to permit an investigation or examination by the Commissioner.
35 (8) Failure to pay any fee or assessment imposed by this Article.
36 (9) Failure to comply with any order of the Commissioner.
37 (10) Insolvency of the licensee.
38 (b) For the purposes of this section, acts of any officer, director, member, trustee,
39 beneficiary, partner, or principal are deemed acts of the licensee.
40 (c) A licensee has the right to cancel and surrender its license, upon notification in a
41 record to the Commissioner.
42 "§ 53-460. Civil penalty.
43 After notice of opportunity for a hearing, the Commissioner may impose a civil penalty upon
44 a person that has violated any of the provisions of this Article or rules adopted under it. The civil
45 penalty shall not exceed one thousand dollars ($1,000) per violation. The clear proceeds of civil
46 penalties provided for in this section shall be remitted to the Civil Penalty and Forfeiture Fund
47 in accordance with G.S. 115C-457.2.
48 "§ 53-461. Injunctions; receivers.
49 If the Commissioner has reasonable cause to believe that a person is violating or is threatening
50 to violate any provision of this Article or rule adopted under it, the Commissioner may enter an
51 order requiring the person to cease and desist from the violation. The Commissioner may also
Page 10 DRS15196-MUf-27

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 seek, and a court may award, an injunction against the person. In accordance with Article 38 of
2 Chapter 1 of the General Statutes, a court may also appoint a receiver for the property and
3 business of the person, including any books, accounts, and records that the court deems necessary
4 to prevent future violations.
5 "§ 53-462. Authority of Attorney General.
6 (a) If the Commissioner determines that a person is in violation, or has violated, any
7 provision of this Article or rule adopted under it, the Commissioner may refer the case to the
8 Attorney General and may request that the Attorney General investigate the violation.
9 (b) With or without a referral, the Attorney General may seek, and a court may award, an
10 injunction for a violation of this Article. If the Attorney General files an action for an injunction,
11 the Attorney General shall provide notice of the action to the Commissioner. The Attorney
12 General may also seek, and a court may award, damages and any other relief allowed by law,
13 including restitution to debtors. The Attorney General shall identify any debtors entitled to relief
14 within 180 days after the date of an order awarding restitution.
15 (c) In an action brought by the Attorney General under this section, the Attorney General
16 is entitled to reasonable attorneys' fees and costs.
17 "§ 53-463. Hearings and appeals.
18 (a) An administrative hearing held by the Commissioner shall be conducted in
19 accordance with Article 3A of Chapter 150B of the General Statutes. The officer presiding at the
20 hearing may be the Commissioner, a deputy commissioner, or another suitable person designated
21 by the Commissioner.
22 (b) A party may appeal a final order of the Commissioner to the State Banking
23 Commission within 30 days after the order. The party shall give a notice of appeal to the
24 Commissioner. The notice of appeal shall state the grounds for the appeal and set forth in
25 numbered order the assignments of error for review by the Commission. Failure to state the
26 grounds for the appeal and assignments of error constitutes grounds to dismiss the appeal. Failure
27 to comply with the briefing schedule provided by the Commission also constitutes grounds to
28 dismiss the appeal. Upon receipt of a notice of appeal, the Commissioner shall, within 30 days
29 of the notice, certify to the Commission the record on appeal.
30 (c) The Chair of the Commission may appoint an appellate review panel of not fewer
31 than three members to review the record on appeal, hear oral arguments, and make a
32 recommended decision to the Commission.
33 (d) A party may petition the Superior Court of Wake County for judicial review of a final
34 order of the Commission within 30 days after the order. A copy of the petition for judicial review
35 shall be served upon the Commissioner pursuant to G.S. 150B-46. The petition shall be placed
36 on the civil issue docket of the court and has precedence over other civil actions. Within 15 days
37 after service of the petition for judicial review, the Commissioner shall certify the record to the
38 Clerk of Superior Court of Wake County. The standard of review of a petition for judicial review
39 of a final order of the Commission is as provided in G.S. 150B-51(b).
40 "§ 53-464. Private right of action; unfair or deceptive trade practice.
41 A person that suffers loss because of another person's violation of this Article or rule adopted
42 under it may bring a civil action against the person. If the plaintiff prevails in the action, a court
43 shall award reasonable attorneys' fees and any other litigation expenses incurred by bringing the
44 action. A violation of this Article or rules adopted under it constitutes an unfair or deceptive trade
45 practice under G.S. 75-1.1.
46 "§ 53-465. Criminal penalty.
47 A violation of this Article is a Class 3 misdemeanor. Each transaction in violation of this
48 Article is a separate offense."
49 SECTION 2. Article 56 of Chapter 14 of the General Statutes is repealed.
50 SECTION 3. This act becomes effective January 1, 2026.
